   private sector, there is concern that the power exercised by
   transnational corporations generates, and is even central to, global
   environmental change. Here, we ask under which conditions transnational
   corporations could either hinder or promote a global shift towards
   sustainability. We show that a handful of transnational corporations
   have become a major force shaping the global intertwined system of
   people and planet. Transnational corporations in agriculture, forestry,
   seafood, cement, minerals and fossil energy cause environmental impacts
   and possess the ability to influence critical functions of the
   biosphere. We review evidence of current practices and identify six
   observed features of change towards `corporate biosphere stewardship',
   with significant potential for upscaling. Actions by transnational
   corporations, if combined with effective public policies and improved
   governmental regulations, could substantially accelerate sustainability
   efforts.}},
