Abstract = {{This article explores the role of actors and agency in the literature on
   sustainability transitions. We reviewed 386 journal articles on
   transition management and sustainability transitions listed in Scopus
   from 1995 to 2014. We investigate the thesis that actors have been
   neglected in this literature in favor of more abstract system concepts.
   Results show that this thesis cannot be confirmed on a general level.
   Rather, we find a variety of different approaches, depending on the
   systemic level, for clustering actors and agency as niche, regime, and
   landscape actors; the societal realm; different levels of governance;
   and intermediaries. We also differentiate between supporting and
   opposing actors. We find that actor roles in transitions are erratic,
   since their roles can change over the course of time, and that actors
   can belong to different categories. We conclude by providing
   recommendations for a comprehensive typology of actors in sustainability
   transitions.}},
